  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Defining the Web App**\n\nI\'m now focusing on the core structure: a React frontend paired with a Python FastAPI backend. The critical piece will be integrating the `abasseyfresh/whisper-large-v3-igbo` model from Hugging Face for English-Igbo translation. It seems this model offers the foundation for the core functionality. I\'m starting to visualize how the data will flow between these components.\n\n\n**Clarifying the Workflow**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on the architecture for the speech translation app. My focus is on leveraging the Whisper model for ASR. Recognizing it\'s a primary audio-to-text model, I\'m thinking of building an audio uploader/recorder. This would feed the FastAPI backend, which would process the audio and return the text. However, a Node.js server seems the existing infrastructure, so I\'m considering the constraints of that environment. Let\'s see if python is even installed.\n\n\n**Adjusting the Approach**\n\nI\'ve hit a snag. The environment is Node.js-based, not Python/FastAPI, as the user requested. My initial architecture won\'t work directly. I\'m now exploring using the Hugging Face Inference API via `@huggingface/inference` from the Node.js backend. Alternatively, I can use the standard `fetch` method if the user provides an API token. I\'m also considering the Gemini API as a translation option. This is necessary because the specified model requires a Python environment I cannot access.\n\n\n**Revising the Strategy**\n\nI\'m now grappling with the resource limitations. I realize that directly hosting the Whisper model is impractical given the Node.js environment and potential memory constraints of the container. My plan has shifted. I\'m prioritizing practicality by explaining the constraints to the user, offering options such as connecting to an external FastAPI backend or utilizing the Gemini API for text translation. I\'m now leaning towards building a React frontend with an Express backend.\n\n\n**Confirming the Backend**\n\nI\'ve clarified the user\'s requirements: they want a full-stack web app with React for the frontend and FastAPI with Python for the backend. Since the current environment doesn\'t support Python, I can\'t host the FastAPI backend directly. My strategy now is to build the React frontend and an Express backend. The Express backend will either mock the API response, provide a Node-based solution, or I\'ll provide the FastAPI code separately for them to run on their own Python environment. The AI Studio server, as a Node.js-based environment, can\'t run a Python backend.\n\n\n**Establishing the Infrastructure**\n\nI\'m now consolidating the architecture. The plan is a React frontend with an Express backend, leveraging Vite for the full-stack setup. I will handle audio capture and translation, and establish proxy routes to either an external FastAPI instance or mock them if necessary. The Express server will handle all API requests, particularly the ones that go to /api/\\*. I will then create the FastAPI backend, and provide it as well, but the backend is only implemented if the user can run it. Port 3000 is the only external port.\n\n\n**Refining the Solution**\n\nI\'m now integrating the Hugging Face Inference API into the plan, since the Python code can\'t be run in this environment. However, the user provided Python code for `abasseyfresh/whisper-large-v3-igbo` and specifies a desire for a FastAPI backend. Therefore, I will include Python code (`main.py` and `requirements.txt`) and design the React UI to interact with it, though it won\'t be runnable in this AI Studio environment. I\'m focusing on the React app\'s requirements: audio recording, audio file upload, and text input for EN <-> IGBO. Note that the Whisper model specializes in ASR, I must ensure a clarification of EN/IGBO.\n\n\n**Clarifying the Model**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on the core functionality. I\'ve realized Whisper is Audio-to-Text. The React app will handle audio input (Igbo or English) and output text. The plan is a single-page React app with the FastAPI backend. I\'ll update the `metadata.json` and install React packages to build the UI in `src/App.tsx`, and I\'ll create `main.py`. I\'ll create the `main.py` back.\n\n\n**Finalizing the Implementation**\n\nI\'m now integrating Express as the full backend to serve the React UI and act as a translation proxy. My Express routes include `/api/transcribe`. This will handle audio input and return placeholder text or call HuggingFace\'s Inference API. I\'m also preparing `fastapi_app.py` for the user\'s Python environment. The React UI will feature a title, audio recording/upload options, and a results text box.\n\n\n**Integrating the Proxy**\n\nI\'m now focusing on the Express backend as a translation proxy and service the React frontend. I\'ve established routes for `/api/transcribe`, so the React app can now send audio for transcription. I\'m preparing an empty FastAPI backend (`fastapi_app.py`) for the user\'s local Python environment. I will design the React UI with audio record/upload features and a text results box to utilize these API routes.\n\n```\n\n\n**Defining the React Frontend**\n\nI\'m now implementing the React UI, and have set up Express as the backend to serve the React application and act as a transcription proxy. I\'ve designed a route `/api/transcribe` which will be the route to accept audio input. The Express backend will return a placeholder response in this AI studio environment. I\'m also preparing a `fastapi_app.py` for their local Python environment for running on their own machine.\n\n\n**Addressing the Model Limitations**\n\nI\'m now clarifying the model\'s capabilities to the user, since `whisper-large-v3-igbo` is ASR, which translates audio to text. I need to explain the model\'s limitations regarding text translation and the need for a different model like NLLB or Gemini for true text-to-text translation. I will clarify this in the UI. I\'ll also implement a React app with a UI featuring recording, file upload, and audio player using Tailwind CSS.\n\n\n**Simplifying the Architecture**\n\nI\'m now shifting to a pure Single-Page Application (SPA) approach with React, simplifying the process for the user. This means the app will be built as a React bundle that makes calls to the FastAPI backend, if available. I will prepare both `fastapi_app.py` and the React frontend and bundle them together as a download. The Express backend is unneeded.\n\n\n**Revising the Delivery**\n\nI\'m now changing the approach based on a stricter interpretation of the user\'s requirements. Since the user wants a FastAPI backend, I\'m now just providing the React frontend and `fastapi_app.py`, allowing the user to run the FastAPI separately. The AI Studio environment allows us to build and preview, but not to fully run a Python/FastAPI backend, however, a Node.js server is the only way to get a preview. I am installing `multer`, `@types/multer`, and `express` as well.\n\n\n**Streamlining the Implementation**\n\nI\'ve decided to streamline the approach further. I\'m now mocking the API call directly within the React frontend, negating the need for an Express backend. I\'m focusing on providing the React frontend and `fastapi_app.py`, allowing the user to run the FastAPI separately. The React code will include a conditional placeholder response, allowing the user to preview a local API call.\n\n\n**Refining the UI/UX**\n\nI\'m now focusing on a React UI with two tabs: \"Speech to Text (Igbo)\" and \"Speech to Text (English)\". I\'m integrating audio recording using the `MediaRecorder` API and implementing audio file upload functionality. I\'ll add a placeholder to clarify that the Whisper model specializes in ASR (audio to text), which requires a new tab to handle English. The UI design will include Tailwind CSS for styling. I\'ll bundle a clean React Vite SPA and FastAPI backend code.\n\n\n**Finalizing the React App**\n\nI\'m now implementing the React app\'s core features. I\'m focusing on audio recording, file upload, transcription display, and tabbed English/Igbo ASR. I\'ll utilize Tailwind CSS for the UI and incorporate the `lucide-react` icons for visual elements. I\'m preparing to handle API calls to a mocked backend initially and transitioning to a live API endpoint, if available.\n\n\n**Integrating Audio Functionality**\n\nI\'m now implementing audio recording and file upload features, using the MediaRecorder API and integrating them into the React UI. I\'ve defined `startRecording` and `stopRecording` functions. These functions will handle the audio stream, data chunks, and recording status. I\'ve also added a `handleFileUpload` function to manage file uploads.\n\n\n**Finalizing the Preview**\n\nI\'m now incorporating a preview response that clarifies how to test the AI model locally. This response explains how to set up the local FastAPI backend with instructions for `pip install` and `uvicorn`. The React code includes a pre-configured `fetch` for the default FastAPI URL (`http://localhost:8000/api/transcribe`) for local testing.\n\n\n**Defining the Local Setup**\n\nI\'m now integrating the preview response for the user to clarify how to test the AI model locally. This response explains the local FastAPI backend setup with instructions for `pip install` and `uvicorn`. The React code has pre-configured `fetch` for the FastAPI URL (`http://localhost:8000/api/transcribe`) for local testing of the web app.\n\n\n**Finalizing the UI Flow**\n\nI\'m now completing the UI with a tabbed interface for Igbo and English ASR. I\'ve integrated audio recording, file upload, and transcription display within the React app. Tailwind CSS is implemented for styling, and I\'ve added a file upload function and state management, and an empty file check before uploading.\n\n\n**Implementing the Recording Logic**\n\nI\'m now incorporating audio recording functionality within the React UI, including `startRecording` and `stopRecording` functions using the `MediaRecorder` API. The audio stream and recording status will be managed. The code will also feature a recording button that changes its icon based on state.\n\n\n**Finalizing the Recording UI**\n\nI\'m now integrating the provided recording UI elements. I\'m focusing on the logic that makes up the user interface by incorporating the \'Record Audio\' section and the \'Upload Audio\' button. The logic is now integrated, ensuring a functional and visually appealing experience for the user. I\'ll make sure these sections will be fully functional.\n\n\n\n**Finalizing the UI**\n\nI\'m now incorporating audio recording and file upload features, using the MediaRecorder API and `handleFileUpload` function. I am focusing on making the React UI functional, including buttons and audio players. The UI elements will display a functional and visually appealing experience to the user.\n\n\n**Completing the React App**\n\nI\'m now integrating the provided code, particularly the \"Clear audio\" and \"Process Audio\" buttons with the recording UI elements. This will finalize the functionality and user experience of the audio recording and uploading features. I\'m focusing on ensuring proper state management and event handling for a seamless user flow.\n\n\n**Integrating the Workflow**\n\nI\'m now integrating the provided code, particularly the \"Clear audio\" and \"Process Audio\" buttons with the recording UI elements. I\'m finalizing the audio recording and uploading features for functionality and user experience. Proper state management and event handling are my current focus.\n\n\n**Refining the API Endpoints**\n\nI\'m now revising the FastAPI code to include `/api/transcribe` and `/api/translate` endpoints, as both are required. I\'m leveraging the Whisper model\'s translation capability through `generate(task=\"translate\")`. However, note that while the Whisper model can translate, its primary function is ASR, therefore this translation won\'t perform the same way as a dedicated translation model like NLLB or Gemini.\n\n\n**Defining the FastAPI Endpoints**\n\nI\'m now implementing the FastAPI endpoints, `/api/transcribe` for ASR and `/api/translate` for EN translation using `generate(task=\"translate\")`. I\'m including temporary file handling for audio uploads and error handling. Note that while this model *can* translate, it is primarily ASR, and will be less accurate. I will clarify this in the React App.\n\n\n"
